 view on the performative power of economic thought - and in this respect moves far beyond merely British perspectives.  afunded by Humboldt-Universität zu Berlin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aPolitical science. 4aBrexit. 4aBritish Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCultural Theory. 4aCulture. 4aEconomic Theory. 4aEurope. 4aFinancial Crisis. 4aGreat Britain. 4aHomo Economicus. 4aNeoliberalism. 4aPower. 4aReal Fiction. 4aReality. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aBrexit.  aBritish Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aEconomic Theory.  aEurope.  aFinancial Crisis.  aGreat Britain.  aHomo Economicus.  aNeoliberalism.  aPower.  aReal Fiction.  aReality.1 aAllen, Jason G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBramall, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButzbach, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenberg, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Jessica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGohrisch, Jana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartell, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStedman, Gesa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat